Let‚Äôs talk about an issue that I‚Äôve noticed at theme parks.
Yesterday I posted about Lennox finally being tall enough for Unikitty Disco Drop @legolandcalifornia 

This ride has a height requirement of 40‚Äù. Which she met every single time she was measured over a 4 day trip. 

Yet, when we attempted to ride Dragon which is also a 40‚Äù height requirement we were turned away as she clearly was not tall enough when being measured. 

This is not unique to Legoland. In fact, this ride in this reel is at @disneyland California Adventure. It also has a 40‚Äù height requirement, she also does not reach the measurement for it. 

There‚Äôs two main issues with theme park height requirements 

1. Legoland does not measure prior to getting in line, so for the instance of the Dragon we made it all the way through before we found out she wasn‚Äôt tall enough and we had to exit. (Talk about a disappointed little girl) 

2. Inconsistency in what they use to measure. 3 different rides, all the same height requirement, all different measurements. (Jumping Jellyfish at DCA also has a 40‚Äù requirement and measures different from Symphony Swings). 

When you have a child who is at the cusp of a new height requirement grouping, the inconsistency in measuring makes it difficult to prepare your child that they may not be able to ride. I‚Äôm a firm believer in not trying to fudge your child‚Äôs height to get on a ride, I don‚Äôt even attempt if I know they aren‚Äôt tall enough. But this time of inconsistency makes that hard.

Lennox did her first 40‚Äù ride this past weekend! For those of you that go to theme parks, you know how big of a deal it is to finally hit 40‚Äù. It unlocks a whole new group of rides!

Children today spend less time outdoors than any other generation. The average American child today is only spending 4 to 7 minutes in unstructured outdoor play per day. This is in sharp comparison to the over 8 hours a week their parents spent outside when they were children. There are many reasons why children today are spending less time outside but one of the biggest reasons is electronic media (the average child today spends 7 ¬Ω hours in front of a screen). 

Unstructured time outside can look like kids playing imaginative games in the woods or in their treehouse, hiking on a trail, looking for treasures along the beach, or climbing a tree in the backyard. The possibilities are endless and there are also countless benefits. 

We have seen our children blossom over the years in terms of their physical abilities, creativeness, and confidence. We attribute a lot of that growth to the unstructured free time they have spent outside.

Children today spend less time outdoors than any other generation. The average American child today is only spending 4 to 7 minutes in unstructured outdoor play per day. This is in sharp comparison to the over 8 hours a week their parents spent outside when they were children. There are many reasons why children today are spending less time outside but one of the biggest reasons is electronic media (the average child today spends 7 ¬Ω hours in front of a screen). 

Unstructured time outside can look like kids playing imaginative games in the woods or in their treehouse, hiking on a trail, looking for treasures along the beach, or climbing a tree in the backyard. The possibilities are endless and there are also countless benefits.

Sleeping on your back in pregnancy.  What have you heard? 

Your body will likely shift to the side if you fall asleep on your back later in pregnancy.  And don‚Äôt freak out if you have slept on your back. 

When you lie on your back, it compresses the blood vessels and can lead to shortness of breath, dizziness, and a possible decrease in blood flow to baby.  That is why sleeping on your side is usually suggested. 

Check out ACOG for more! And be sure to ask your doc for tips!

Let‚Äôs chat laboring down. 

There has been a lot of recent studies on this topic.  Some state that there is no benefit to delaying pushing once the patient is completely dilated. 

I agree that if the patient is just lying and not moving to help facilitate rotation, then laboring down and just waiting for contractions to push baby out probably won‚Äôt work.  BUT, if a baby is still high in the pelvis, then helping mom get into other positions to help bring baby down, imo definitely helps with descent. 

The key is to make sure that you are being actively managed in labor.  In other words, your nurse should be moving you side to side and utilizing the peanut ball to help baby rotate.  If your nurse isn‚Äôt doing that, make sure to ask your support person to help. 

I will share more information on this topic in stories and more posts, so be sure to tune in!

Social media tips for sensitive creators:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Create before you consume: Keep your eyes on your own work! Getting inspired is AWESOME, but in order to stay original and true to YOU‚Ä¶create your own content before checking out what everyone else is doing!

2Ô∏è‚É£ Remember, your unique voice matters: You‚Äôre most likely not going to be the first person ever doing what you‚Äôre doing. However, you‚Äôre the only person with your unique vision, voice, & style.

Someone needs to hear what YOU have to say in only the way that YOU can say it. And THAT MATTERS!!

3Ô∏è‚É£ Set boundaries around your social media time: When you‚Äôre a sensitive person you can get more overwhelmed than others and too much social media can DEFINITELY get overwhelming. So make sure to set some boundaries around it!!

This can look like: only answering DM‚Äôs for an hour a day, no Instagram until after your morning tasks are complete, no phone after 7 pm, etc.. These boundaries can look different for everyone!

5Ô∏è‚É£ Know when to cut the cord: The great thing about social media is that it allows us to connect with SO many people. The hard thing ab out it? It allows us to connect with SO many people‚Ä¶which can sometimes feel draining.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Have fun and lean into your creativity: THIS is one of the most important tips I can share! I experienced a MAJOR shift in my social media FEELINGS when I fully leaned into having more fun with my content and getting creative with it.

Instead of making every single post feel like a huge, scary deal‚Ä¶view it as an experiment! Some posts work, some don‚Äôt. Learn from it and have fun!

Trust me, ITS NOT THAT SERIOUS!!

Putting yourself out there on social media isn‚Äôt easy! (Especially for the sensitive). But I try to keep stepping outside of my comfort zone because‚Ä¶
üëâüèº I know my WHY?
üëâüèº I know my message IS important.

One of my biggest fears is getting hacked on Instagram & losing my account, followers, content, EVERYTHING!!! 

It‚Äôs so crazy how many people lose their account because they didn‚Äôt take the time to protect it!! 

Just last year there were over 70K creator profiles who were compromised by hackers! 

So what can you do?? Here are a FEW TIPS:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Turn on 2 factor authentication! 2 factor authentication is usually the only way to get your account back IF you were hacked!

When you have 2-fac authorization set up, you‚Äôll receive a notification or be asked to enter a special login code when someone tries logging into your account from a device IG doesn‚Äôt recognize.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Watch for the warning signs- IG will NEVER ask you for your password so do NOT fall for that trick!

‚ÄúPhishing‚Äù is when someone tries to get access to your IG account by sending you a suspicious message or link that asks for your personal information while making you think it‚Äôs official! (Sometimes claiming that your account will be banned or deleted if you don‚Äôt follow directions)

Emails from IG/FB  about your account will only come from: mail.Instagram.com or facebookmail,com! 

This type of phishing is happening with A LOT of people lately. If it happens to you and you‚Äôre in doubt, DONT CLICK! 

üëâüèº Go check your Account Status in Settings. You will see if you‚Äôve posted anything that is affecting your Account Status (this is the only way IG informs you on Violations so don‚Äôt trust any other source!)

3Ô∏è‚É£ Pick a strong password!! Use a combo of numbers, letters and punctuation marks & changr your password regularly! 

üëâüèºNever share your password! Don‚Äôt save them to your phone, note them down on paper to be safe!

‚ÄúBUT YOU DONT LOOK SICK?‚Äù IS NOT ALWAYS A COMPlMENT!!!

Living with an invisible illness can be a bit of a double-edged sword. On one hand, it can be nice to keep your health issues private, only sharing them with others when you‚Äôre comfortable doing so.

But on the other hand, many people hold the misconception that you must ‚Äúlook‚Äù sick in order to be sick ‚Äì which can lead to unfair judgments and false accusations.

Some of the most common phrases people with invisible illness hear are ‚ÄúBut you don‚Äôt look sick‚Ä¶‚Äù and ‚ÄúBut you look fine!‚Äù Although these comments are usually not at all ill-intentioned, they can still be frustrating, hurtful and isolating because they demonstrate a lack of understanding about chronic illness.

Knowing how to respond in these situations can be tricky. In some cases, the comment may provide an opportunity to educate the person about the realities of invisible illness. Other times, you may not feel comfortable going into detail ‚Äì maybe you don‚Äôt know the person that well, or are just aren‚Äôt in the mood to explain. And that‚Äôs OK, too.

However you decide to respond, it maybe helpful to have a few lines prepared ahead of time so you‚Äôre not caught off-guard!

üëâüèº ‚ÄúWell thanks, I bought my ‚Äòlook fine‚Äô mask at the doctor‚Äôs office, but he still hasn‚Äôt cured my chronic illness? What am I even paying him for?! üôÑ

üëâüèº ‚ÄúI know, but I‚Äôve been sick for so long I know how to look ‚ÄòChronic Illness Chic‚Äô‚Ä¶ you should have seen me before I was sick!‚Äù

Let me explain: I‚Äôve heard it said that ‚ÄúWe all have the same 24 hours in a day!‚Äù

And I have to kindly disagree! This quote in its varying forms, is meant to be motivational‚Ä¶.

And it is. Every time I read it I feel motivated to DO MORE. Even Beyonc√© only has 24 hours in a day, right?

And yes, these quotes can help inspire us to do more- but they can also be damaging. Causing us to compare to others.

While it‚Äôs true that Beyonc√© does have the same 24 hours as myself, our 24 hours are NOT the same! 

I do not have a team of assistants & all that comes with being the queen B!! If I did, then my 24 hours would most likely look vastly different to how they currently do.

My day will also look different to that of a wealthy single bachelor, a single parent, someone without any support system, someone who has an entire team working their business, etc etc!!

It is true that if you prioritize the important tasks, if you sacrifice certain things like watching Netflix every evening, you can achieve more.

We all have the capability to work towards our goals if we organize our time & prioritize and make some sacrifices.

But please know that if you are struggling, or want to watch Netflix, you are NOT failing!!! 

At the moment, I am trying to run my business from home while having a chronic illness & learning to walk on my own. Between physical therapy, infusions, and other appointments. This means that I‚Äôm not able to do as much as I would like.

I could work through til 2 am, however I‚Äôm not sure this would be if any benefit to anyone, especially myself. 

Some things that happen during your day will be choices you make, like choosing to spend your evening having quality time with your partner/family instead of working.

Things like caring for your children, cleaning your home, cooking etc are not things you can choose not to do without neglecting your responsibilities.

Our use of those 24 hours will all be different depending on our circumstances. We all do have 24 hours in a day. But we DO NOT have the same 24 hours!

There are many grounding & self care practices to help survivors of trauma learn how to overcome the stress responses that maybe not serving you well.

üçÇ Pumpkin Chocolate Chips Bars - SAVE this recipe! üòç

My daughter helped me make these and said it was the best treat I ever made - this was even after she watched me tweak my old recipe to make them ‚Äúhealthier‚Äù üôåüèª 

We also had a house full of 5th grade boys who tried them and I think they would have eaten the whole pan if I let them üòÇ They are gooey and DELICIOUS and AMAZING. ‚§µÔ∏è

1 cup unsalted organic butter, room temperature
3/4 cup coconut sugar
3/4 cup honey
1 egg
2 teaspoons vanilla extract
1 cup canned pumpkin puree
2 cups white whole wheat flour
1 tablespoon pumpkin pie spice
1 teaspoon baking soda
3/4 teaspoon salt
1 package (12 oz) semisweet chocolate chips

Preheat oven to 350 degrees and spray a 9√ó13 baking sheet with non-stick cooking spray. In the bowl of a stand mixer, cream butter and coconut sugar and honey until smooth. Add egg and vanilla and beat until combined. Mix in pumpkin puree.

Combine the flour, pumpkin pie spice, baking soda and salt in a small bowl. On low speed, mix dry ingredients into wet until just combined. Fold in chocolate chips.

Spread batter evenly in pan and bake until a toothpick inserted in the center comes out almost clean, about 30-35 minutes. Cool completely in pan. Cut into 24 squares.
